Both Idea 0 (Latent Action-State Transformer, LAST) and Idea 1 (Belief-Space Procedural Transformer, BSPT) are highly novel and technically sophisticated, proposing differentiable, entity-free frameworks for modeling procedural text understanding through latent state dynamics. However, when evaluating against the provided related work and assessing novelty with a harsh critic’s eye, key distinctions emerge.

Idea 0 introduces implicit state transitions using differentiable reasoning and advantage estimation to guide attention in a transformer, leveraging procedural coherence as a self-supervised signal. While innovative, its core mechanism—modeling latent state changes and using GAE-style signals for attention—is conceptually close to existing work in differentiable dynamic systems and reinforcement learning-inspired attention mechanisms. The use of advantage estimation for attention modulation has precedents in adaptive computation time (ACT) models and some RL-NLP hybrids, which slightly reduces its novelty edge.

In contrast, Idea 1 (BSPT) makes a stronger conceptual leap by explicitly framing procedural understanding as *belief revision under partial observability*, using a neural approximation of Bayesian filtering in a continuous latent space. This is not merely latent state tracking but full belief-state maintenance over distributions, which allows for principled handling of uncertainty, ambiguity, and missing information. Crucially, it integrates soft Metric Temporal Logic (MTL) constraints as differentiable penalties during training—a mechanism directly inspired by formal methods in stream reasoning—but adapted to neural procedural understanding. Paper 1 discusses MTL under uncertainty in symbolic stream reasoning, but does so in non-neural, logic-based systems. BSPT bridges this gap by making MTL differentiable and embedding it into a neural belief updater, which is unprecedented in NLP or procedural reasoning. Furthermore, Papers 2, 4, and 5 touch on belief revision and uncertainty in reasoning, but none integrate these ideas into procedural text *with temporal structure* and *without symbolic representations*. BSPT uniquely combines belief-space dynamics, differentiable MTL, and advantage-conditioned attention into a unified, end-to-end trainable model for procedural coherence—offering a new paradigm that is both more expressive and more robust than prior art.

Thus, while both ideas are strong, **Idea 1** demonstrates higher novelty due to its integration of formal reasoning under uncertainty with deep procedural modeling, going beyond latent states to full probabilistic beliefs and constrained differentiable reasoning—contributing a significantly new direction not covered in the cited literature.

