Both Idea 0 (LAST) and Idea 1 (BSPT) propose innovative, entity-free approaches to modeling action and information flow in procedural texts using differentiable latent state dynamics. However, novelty must be assessed not only in terms of technical design but also in relation to existing literature.

Idea 0 introduces a "Latent Action-State Transformer" that models procedural flow via differentiable state transitions and uses advantage estimation to guide attention—inspired by reinforcement learning—to capture causal dependencies without explicit entities. While this is a strong idea, the core concept of modeling procedural text as a sequence of implicit state changes has precedents in prior work such as ProPara and neural process networks. The use of GAE-style signals for attention modulation is creative, but similar ideas of using trajectory coherence and contrastive objectives for step ordering have been explored in entity-aware or entity-tracking frameworks.

Idea 1, BSPT, goes significantly further by framing procedural understanding as *belief-space reasoning under partial observability*, explicitly modeling uncertainty through a learned probabilistic belief state akin to Bayesian filtering. This is a more fundamental departure from existing paradigms. Crucially, it integrates soft Metric Temporal Logic (MTL) constraints as differentiable penalties during training—a mechanism not seen in standard NLP models. Paper 1 discusses MTL under uncertainty in stream reasoning, but it operates in symbolic, logic-based systems and assumes formal state representations; BSPT instead learns these dynamics end-to-end in natural language with no symbolic input, making it distinct. Furthermore, the combination of belief updating, advantage-conditioned attention, and differentiable MTL constraints creates a novel architecture that redefines procedural reasoning as incremental belief refinement—an interpretability-rich, scalable framework for open-world instruction following.

While Paper 4 touches on belief revision in LMs, it focuses on evaluating models rather than proposing a new reasoning architecture. None of the other papers address the integration of temporal logic, belief states, and differentiable reasoning in procedural text understanding. Thus, BSPT represents a more substantial and novel contribution, especially for high-impact venues focused on reasoning, planning, or robust NLP.

